    "body": "It's a bit outside my zone of comfort, but I think the answer is \"No\" -- it can be `0` or `1`, but depending on whether it's in canonical form or not, it can also be `27/28` on mainnet (different for other networks), if it's used for replay protection. \r\n\r\nWhat I mean by canonical form: The transaction `V` is  used for replay protection, but the actual `V` value that goes into the crypto libraries is 'canonicalized', and turned into `1` or `0`. \r\n\r\nI'm not really that crypto-savvy, so I may have gotten something wrong here.  ",
